      "\n    -- Use the fact that the sum of reciprocals of the first n positive integers is greater than or equal to the natural logarithm of (n + 1)\n    have hРѓЃ : Рѕђ (n : РёЋ), Real.log ((n : РёЮ) + 1) РЅц РѕЉ k Рѕѕ Icc 1 n, (k : РёЮ)РЂ╗┬╣ := by\n      intro n\n      induction n with\n      | zero =>\n        norm_num\n      | succ n ih =>\n        rw [Icc_self]\n        simp_all [Icc_self]\n        <;>\n        (try norm_num at * <;> linarith) <;>\n        (try {\n          simp_all [Finset.sum_Icc_succ_top, Nat.cast_add, Nat.cast_one, add_assoc]\n          <;>\n          (try norm_num at * <;> linarith) <;>\n          (try {\n            have hРѓё : 0 < (n.succ : РёЮ) := by positivity\n            have hРѓЁ : Real.log ((n.succ : РёЮ) + 1) РЅц (n.succ : РёЮ)РЂ╗┬╣ + Real.log ((n.succ : РёЮ)) := by\n              have hРѓє : Real.log ((n.succ : РёЮ) + 1) - Real.log ((n.succ : РёЮ)) РЅц (n.succ : РёЮ)РЂ╗┬╣ := by\n                have hРѓЄ : Real.log ((n.succ : РёЮ) + 1) - Real.log ((n.succ : РёЮ)) = Real.log (((n.succ : РёЮ) + 1) / (n.succ : РёЮ)) := by\n                  rw [Real.log_div (by positivity) (by positivity)]\n                  <;> field_simp [Real.log_mul, Real.log_pow]\n                  <;> ring_nf\n                  <;> norm_num\n                rw [hРѓЄ]\n                have hРѓѕ : Real.log (((n.succ : РёЮ) + 1) / (n.succ : РёЮ)) РЅц (n.succ : РёЮ)РЂ╗┬╣ := by\n                  have hРѓЅ : ((n.succ : РёЮ) + 1) / (n.succ : РёЮ) = 1 + 1 / (n.succ : РёЮ) := by\n                    field_simp\n                    <;> ring_nf\n                    <;> field_simp\n                    <;> ring_nf\n                  rw [hРѓЅ]\n                  have hРѓЂРѓђ : Real.log (1 + 1 / (n.succ : РёЮ)) РЅц 1 / (n.succ : РёЮ) := by\n                    have hРѓЂРѓЂ : 0 < (1 : РёЮ) / (n.succ : РёЮ) := by positivity\n                    have hРѓЂРѓѓ : Real.log (1 + 1 / (n.succ : РёЮ)) РЅц 1 / (n.succ : РёЮ) := by\n                      linarith [Real.log_le_sub_one_of_pos (by positivity : 0 < (1 + 1 / (n.succ : РёЮ) : РёЮ))]\n                    linarith\n                  linarith\n                linarith\n              have hРѓЂРѓђ : Real.log ((n.succ : РёЮ) + 1) РЅц (n.succ : РёЮ)РЂ╗┬╣ + Real.log ((n.succ : РёЮ)) := by linarith\n              linarith\n            have hРѓЂРѓЂ : Real.log ((n.succ : РёЮ)) РЅц РѕЉ k in Finset.Icc 1 n, (k : РёЮ)РЂ╗┬╣ := by\n              simpa using ih\n            linarith\n          })\n        })\n    exact hРѓЃ n\n  -- Combine the inequalities to get the final result\n  linarith",
      " `Real.log n + 1/n - 1`, but this doesn't directly help. A better approach is to use that for each `k РЅЦ 1`,\n\n```\n1/k РЅц РѕФ_{k-1}^{k} 1/t dt = log k - log (k - 1),\n```\n\nbut this is not true for `k = 1` because `log 0` is undefined. \n\nAlternatively, we can use that for `x РЅЦ 1`,\n\n```\nlog x РЅц x - 1.\n```\n\nBut in our case, `x < n + 1`, so `x - 1 < n`, but the sum of reciprocals up to `n` is about `log n + ╬│`, which is less than `n` only for `n РЅЦ 2`. This approach might not be directly helpful either.\n\nA much better strategy is to realize that since `x < n + 1`, we can use the fact that `log x < log(n + 1)` and then use bounds involving the integral of `1/t`. Specifically,\n\n`log(n + 1) РЅц 1 + РѕЉ_{k=2}^{n} 1/k`.\n\nBut to make this rigorous, we need to prove that `log(n + 1) РЅц 1 + РѕЉ_{k=2}^{n} 1/k`. We can prove this by induction on `n` or by using integrals. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps the simplest approach is to note that for `k РЅЦ 1`, `1/k РЅЦ РѕФ_{k}^{k+1} 1/t dt`, because `1/t РЅц 1/k` on `[k, k+1]`. Summing over `k` from `1` to `n` gives:\n\n`РѕЉ_{k=1}^n 1/k РЅЦ log(n + 1)`. \n\nBut this contradicts the assumption `x < n + 1`, because `log x < log(n + 1)` and we would have `log x < РѕЉ_{k=1}^n 1/k`, which is not what we want. \n\nActually, the inequality is reversed: `1/k РЅЦ РѕФ_{k}^{k+1} 1/t dt`, so `РѕЉ_{k=1}^n 1/k РЅЦ log(n + 1)`. \n\nHowever, we have `x < n + 1`, so `log x < log(n + 1)`, and thus `log x < РѕЉ_{k=1}^n 1/k`. But we want `log x РЅц РѕЉ_{k=1}^n 1/k`. \n\nHmm, this does not directly help because we need a non-strict inequality. \n\nBut perhaps there is a simpler approach: since `x РЅЦ n`, then `log x РЅЦ log n`, and we can try to prove that `log n РЅц РѕЉ_{k=1}^n 1/k`. But again, the sum of reciprocals from `1` to `n` is about `log n + ╬│`, so `log n РЅц РѕЉ_{k=1}^n 1/k` is true, and combining it with `log x РЅЦ log n` would give `log x РЅц РѕЉ_{k=1}^n 1/k`, but we have `log x РЅЦ log n` and `log n РЅц РѕЉ_{k=1