`n : РёЋ`, so `n = 2`, `x Рѕѕ [2, 3)`.\n\nBut if we take `x = 1.9`, `n = 1`, `x Рѕѕ [1, 2)`, `log x РЅѕ 0.6418 РЅц 1`. \n\nBut for `n = 1`, `x Рѕѕ [1, 2)`, `log x` is `РЅц 1`, which is correct (`log 2 РЅѕ 0.693 РЅц 1`). \n\nSo in fact, it's only wrong in the case `n РЅЦ 2` if we take `x` closer to `n + 1`, e.g., `x = 2.9`, `n = 2`.\n\nThen `log 2.9 РЅѕ 1.06066` and sum is `1 + 0.5 = 1.5`, which is fine (`1.06066 РЅц 1.5`). \n\nHmm, but `x = 2.718`, `log 2.718 РЅѕ 1.00005`, and sum `1.5`, which is fine (`1.00005 РЅц 1.5`). \n\nMy mistake: in the example `x = e`, I thought `log e РЅѕ 1.609`, but `e РЅѕ 2.718`, `log e = 1`.\n\nOops! I was confusing `log` base 10 and natural log!\n\n`log e = 1`, and `sum_{k=1}^2 1/k = 1.5`, so `1 РЅц 1.5` is correct.\n\nAnother example: `x = 2`, `n = 1`, then `x Рѕѕ [1, 2)`, but `x РЅЦ 1`, `x < 2`, but `x = 2`, contradiction! \n\nOh, no: if `n = 1`, then `hxge : x РЅЦ 1`, `hxlt : x < 2`, and `x = 2` does not satisfy `x < 2`. \n\nBut if `x = 2`, the hypothesis is not satisfied. \n\nFor `n = 1`, the condition is `x Рѕѕ [1, 2)`.\n\nIn this interval, `log x РЅц 1`.\n\nBut `x = 1`, `log 1 = 0 РЅц 1`.\n\n`x РЅѕ 1.9`, `log x РЅѕ 0.6418 РЅц 1`.\n\nThe maximum of `log x` on `[1, 2)` is `log(2) РЅѕ 0.693 < 1`. \n\nSimilarly, for `n = 2`, the interval is `[2, 3)` and the sum is `1 + 1/2 = 1.5`.\n\nBut `log x` on `[2, 3)` is increasing, and at `x Рєњ 3РЂ╗`, `log x Рєњ log 3 РЅѕ 1.0986 < 1.5`.\n\n`log 2 РЅѕ 0.693 < 1.5`.\n\nSimilarly, for `n = 3`, `x Рѕѕ [3, 4)`, sum `1 + 1/2 + 1/3 РЅѕ 1.833`, and `log x РЅц log 4 РЅѕ 1.386 < 1.833`.\n\nIt seems that the statement might actually be true. \n\nBut why? \n\nBecause `x < n + 1`, so `log x < log (n + 1)`, and we need to show that `log (n + 1) РЅц sum_{k=1}^n 1/k`. \n\nBut this is equivalent to `log(n + 1) РЅц H_n`, where `H_n` is the harmonic number. \n\nBut `H_n РЅЦ log(n + 1)` is equivalent to `H_n - log(n) РЅЦ log(1 + 1/n)`.\n\nWe know that `H_n - log n` decreases to the Euler-Mascheroni constant `╬│ 